OPENING Narrative Writing Since you began school, you’ve used your imagination to write many stories. These stories are called “narratives.” Today you’ll write a narrative so that your teacher can see how much you have learned since the beginning of the year about writing a good story.
Write a brief response to the following question.
What do you know about narrative writing? Share with the class.

Write a brief response to the following question.
What do you know about narrative writing?
Now you will write your narrative. Remember that a is a story about events, both real and imaginary.
You will have 20 minutes to write your narrative.

In this unit, instead of reading your regular Book Club book, you will select a fantasy book to read independently. You will get to talk with others about your book, as you do during your regular Book Club.
One of your Unit Accomplishments for this unit is to read a fantasy text and write a response to it. Review the Unit Accomplishments to find out the details of this assignment.
Preview the possibilities your teacher suggests for your book choice.
Your homework assignment is to talk to friends and family members about fantasy books they would recommend. Find out what they like about the books they recommend.
Make a short list of titles from people’s suggestions and think about which one you might like to read in your Fantasy Book Club.
